('chunk_369d03d24c9c14e0ef','file_c7904436411b2e478c','music.md','3. Sub-topic A — Warm-ups','**Why warm-ups matter:** The voice is produced by muscles (the vocal folds) and supported by breath. Just like a runner stretches before a race, a singer warms up to increase blood flow, relax the throat and jaw, engage the breath, and prevent strain or injury. Warming up also focuses the mind and tunes the ear before singing repertoire.','{"sub":1,"topic":1,"warm":2,"ups":2,"why":1,"matter":1,"the":6,"voice":1,"produced":1,"muscles":1,"vocal":1,"folds":1,"and":4,"supported":1,"breath":2,"just":1,"like":1,"runner":1,"stretches":1,"before":2,"race":1,"singer":1,"warms":1,"increase":1,"blood":1,"flow":1,"relax":1,"throat":1,"jaw":1,"engage":1,"prevent":1,"strain":1,"injury":1,"warming":1,"also":1,"focuses":1,"mind":1,"tunes":1,"ear":1,"singing":1,"repertoire":1}'::jsonb),
('chunk_31334beaf1267e7fb8','file_c7904436411b2e478c','music.md','3.1 Breathing exercises','- **Definition:** Controlled breathing drills that activate the **diaphragm** (the dome-shaped muscle below the lungs) so the singer has a steady, supported air stream.
- **How-to cue:** Stand tall. Place a hand on your belly. Breathe in silently through the nose so the belly expands outward (not the shoulders). Exhale slowly on a steady "sss" for 4, then 8, then 12 counts — keep the hiss even to the very end.
- **Real example:** "Hissing snake" — inhale for 4, hiss out for 8, aiming for a smooth, unbroken sound.
- **Why it matters:** Steady breath = steady tone, longer phrases, and better pitch control.
- **Common misconception:** *"You breathe with your shoulders / chest."* **Correction:** Good singing breath is low and expands the belly and lower ribs; raised shoulders create tension and shallow air.
- **Practice cue:** Watch your shoulders in a mirror — if they lift when you inhale, drop them and breathe into your belly instead.','{"breathing":2,"exercises":1,"definition":1,"controlled":1,"drills":1,"that":1,"activate":1,"the":10,"diaphragm":1,"dome":1,"shaped":1,"muscle":1,"below":1,"lungs":1,"singer":1,"has":1,"steady":4,"supported":1,"air":2,"stream":1,"how":1,"cue":2,"stand":1,"tall":1,"place":1,"hand":1,"your":4,"belly":4,"breathe":3,"silently":1,"through":1,"nose":1,"expands":2,"outward":1,"not":1,"shoulders":4,"exhale":1,"slowly":1,"sss":1,"for":4,"then":2,"counts":1,"keep":1,"hiss":2,"even":1,"very":1,"end":1,"real":1,"example":1,"hissing":1,"snake":1,"inhale":2,"out":1,"aiming":1,"smooth":1,"unbroken":1,"sound":1,"why":1,"matters":1,"breath":2,"tone":1,"longer":1,"phrases":1,"and":5,"better":1,"pitch":1,"control":1,"common":1,"misconception":1,"you":2,"with":1,"chest":1,"correction":1,"good":1,"singing":1,"low":1,"lower":1,"ribs":1,"raised":1,"create":1,"tension":1,"shallow":1,"practice":1,"watch":1,"mirror":1,"they":1,"lift":1,"when":1,"drop":1,"them":1,"into":1,"instead":1}'::jsonb),
('chunk_aa67490c415aa88681','file_c7904436411b2e478c','music.md','3.2 Vocal sirens / glissando','- **Definition:** A **glissando** (or "siren") is a smooth, continuous slide from a low pitch up to a high pitch and back, with no separate steps between notes.
- **How-to cue:** On an "ng" or "oo" sound, glide gently like a siren from your lowest comfortable note to your highest and back down. Keep it light — no pushing.
- **Real example:** Sliding "oooo" from low to high like an ambulance siren.
- **Analogy:** Like stretching an elastic band slowly and evenly — gentle and gradual, never a sudden yank.
- **Why it matters:** Sirens gently connect your low ("chest") and high ("head") voice, warming the whole range smoothly.
- **Common misconception:** *"Warm up loudly to get power."* **Correction:** Warm-ups should be light and easy; loud pushing on a cold voice risks strain.
- **Practice cue:** Keep the slide connected — imagine one unbroken line, not a staircase.','{"vocal":1,"sirens":2,"glissando":2,"definition":1,"siren":3,"smooth":1,"continuous":1,"slide":2,"from":3,"low":3,"pitch":2,"high":3,"and":6,"back":2,"with":1,"separate":1,"steps":1,"between":1,"notes":1,"how":1,"cue":2,"sound":1,"glide":1,"gently":2,"like":3,"your":3,"lowest":1,"comfortable":1,"note":1,"highest":1,"down":1,"keep":2,"light":2,"pushing":2,"real":1,"example":1,"sliding":1,"oooo":1,"ambulance":1,"analogy":1,"stretching":1,"elastic":1,"band":1,"slowly":1,"evenly":1,"gentle":1,"gradual":1,"never":1,"sudden":1,"yank":1,"why":1,"matters":1,"connect":1,"chest":1,"head":1,"voice":2,"warming":1,"the":2,"whole":1,"range":1,"smoothly":1,"common":1,"misconception":1,"warm":2,"loudly":1,"get":1,"power":1,"correction":1,"ups":1,"should":1,"easy":1,"loud":1,"cold":1,"risks":1,"strain":1,"practice":1,"connected":1,"imagine":1,"one":1,"unbroken":1,"line":1,"not":1,"staircase":1}'::jsonb),
('chunk_66b34814d01b7faf7c','file_c7904436411b2e478c','music.md','3.3 Scale warm-ups','- **Definition:** Singing short scale patterns (often on solfege or "ah/ee/oo") to warm the voice and train the ear for pitch.
- **How-to cue:** Sing a five-note pattern "do-re-mi-fa-sol-fa-mi-re-do," then move it up a step and repeat, keeping vowels tall and even.
- **Real example:** A rising and falling major five-note scale climbing by half-steps across the class range.
- **Why it matters:** Builds pitch accuracy, evenness of tone across the range, and vowel consistency.
- **Common misconception:** *"Scales are boring exercises with no purpose."* **Correction:** Scales train the ear and voice together — they are the "stretching and strengthening" that make songs easier.
- **Practice cue:** Match each note exactly to a keyboard or drone; listen before you sing.

