('chunk_3014d15b2d8645b998','file_c7904436411b2e478c','music.md','4. Sub-topic B — Vocal Technique','Good singing is a coordinated system: **posture supports breath, breath supports tone, and shaping (diction) makes it clear.**','{"sub":1,"topic":1,"vocal":1,"technique":1,"good":1,"singing":1,"coordinated":1,"system":1,"posture":1,"supports":2,"breath":2,"tone":1,"and":1,"shaping":1,"diction":1,"makes":1,"clear":1}'::jsonb),
('chunk_c4fb9874bc1062dff5','file_c7904436411b2e478c','music.md','4.1 Singing posture','- **Definition:** The aligned, balanced body position that lets breath flow freely.
- **How-to cue:** Feet shoulder-width apart, weight balanced; knees soft (not locked); spine tall; shoulders relaxed and down; chest comfortably open ("noble" posture); head level, chin parallel to the floor.
- **Why it matters:** A collapsed chest or slumped spine squashes the breath and dulls the tone.
- **Common misconception:** *"Standing stiff and rigid is good posture."* **Correction:** Posture should be tall but **relaxed and flexible** — tension anywhere (jaw, neck, shoulders) hurts the sound.
- **Practice cue:** Imagine a string gently lifting the crown of your head toward the ceiling.','{"singing":1,"posture":4,"definition":1,"the":7,"aligned":1,"balanced":2,"body":1,"position":1,"that":1,"lets":1,"breath":2,"flow":1,"freely":1,"how":1,"cue":2,"feet":1,"shoulder":1,"width":1,"apart":1,"weight":1,"knees":1,"soft":1,"not":1,"locked":1,"spine":2,"tall":2,"shoulders":2,"relaxed":2,"and":4,"down":1,"chest":2,"comfortably":1,"open":1,"noble":1,"head":2,"level":1,"chin":1,"parallel":1,"floor":1,"why":1,"matters":1,"collapsed":1,"slumped":1,"squashes":1,"dulls":1,"tone":1,"common":1,"misconception":1,"standing":1,"stiff":1,"rigid":1,"good":1,"correction":1,"should":1,"but":1,"flexible":1,"tension":1,"anywhere":1,"jaw":1,"neck":1,"hurts":1,"sound":1,"practice":1,"imagine":1,"string":1,"gently":1,"lifting":1,"crown":1,"your":1,"toward":1,"ceiling":1}'::jsonb),
('chunk_0e086a3d3bcb604cc9','file_c7904436411b2e478c','music.md','4.2 Diaphragmatic breathing (breath support)','- **Definition:** Using the diaphragm and lower-rib muscles to control a steady stream of air ("support").
- **How-to cue:** Inhale low (belly expands), then sing while keeping the ribs from collapsing too fast — as if gently holding the expansion.
- **Analogy:** Support is like slowly letting air out of a balloon by pinching the neck — controlled, not all at once.
- **Why it matters:** Support gives steady pitch, longer phrases, and dynamic control without strain.
- **Common misconception:** *"Take the biggest breath possible before every phrase."* **Correction:** You need an *appropriate*, low, relaxed breath — over-filling creates tension.
- **Practice cue:** Sing a phrase and try to end it with a little breath still in reserve.','{"diaphragmatic":1,"breathing":1,"breath":4,"support":4,"definition":1,"using":1,"the":5,"diaphragm":1,"and":3,"lower":1,"rib":1,"muscles":1,"control":2,"steady":2,"stream":1,"air":2,"how":1,"cue":2,"inhale":1,"low":2,"belly":1,"expands":1,"then":1,"sing":2,"while":1,"keeping":1,"ribs":1,"from":1,"collapsing":1,"too":1,"fast":1,"gently":1,"holding":1,"expansion":1,"analogy":1,"like":1,"slowly":1,"letting":1,"out":1,"balloon":1,"pinching":1,"neck":1,"controlled":1,"not":1,"all":1,"once":1,"why":1,"matters":1,"gives":1,"pitch":1,"longer":1,"phrases":1,"dynamic":1,"without":1,"strain":1,"common":1,"misconception":1,"take":1,"biggest":1,"possible":1,"before":1,"every":1,"phrase":2,"correction":1,"you":1,"need":1,"appropriate":1,"relaxed":1,"over":1,"filling":1,"creates":1,"tension":1,"practice":1,"try":1,"end":1,"with":1,"little":1,"still":1,"reserve":1}'::jsonb),
('chunk_6e59d737c07c4711c8','file_c7904436411b2e478c','music.md','4.3 Diction / articulation','- **Definition:** The clear pronunciation of **vowels** (which carry the tone) and **consonants** (which carry the words).
- **How-to cue:** Sustain sound on tall, open vowels; make consonants crisp and quick so they don''t interrupt the line. Keep the jaw loose and the tongue relaxed.
- **Real example:** In "night," hold the "ah" vowel and add a light, late "t" at the very end.
- **Why it matters:** Diction lets the audience understand the lyrics and helps the ensemble stay together.
- **Common misconception:** *"Sing loudly and people will understand the words."* **Correction:** Clarity comes from crisp consonants and tall vowels, not volume.
- **Practice cue:** Speak the lyrics in rhythm first, then sing them keeping the same clarity.','{"diction":2,"articulation":1,"definition":1,"the":14,"clear":1,"pronunciation":1,"vowels":3,"which":2,"carry":2,"tone":1,"and":7,"consonants":3,"words":2,"how":1,"cue":2,"sustain":1,"sound":1,"tall":2,"open":1,"make":1,"crisp":2,"quick":1,"they":1,"don":1,"interrupt":1,"line":1,"keep":1,"jaw":1,"loose":1,"tongue":1,"relaxed":1,"real":1,"example":1,"night":1,"hold":1,"vowel":1,"add":1,"light":1,"late":1,"very":1,"end":1,"why":1,"matters":1,"lets":1,"audience":1,"understand":2,"lyrics":2,"helps":1,"ensemble":1,"stay":1,"together":1,"common":1,"misconception":1,"sing":2,"loudly":1,"people":1,"will":1,"correction":1,"clarity":2,"comes":1,"from":1,"not":1,"volume":1,"practice":1,"speak":1,"rhythm":1,"first":1,"then":1,"them":1,"keeping":1,"same":1}'::jsonb),
('chunk_9900641f0b72ccaae0','file_c7904436411b2e478c','music.md','4.4 Tone quality / resonance','- **Definition:** The **timbre** or "colour" of the voice — how warm, bright, clear, or focused it sounds. Resonance is how sound vibrates and amplifies in the throat, mouth, and head spaces.
- **How-to cue:** Keep vowels tall and open, soft palate lifted (as in the start of a yawn), throat relaxed and free.
- **Analogy:** Resonance is like the hollow body of a guitar — the same string sounds fuller because of the space it vibrates in.
- **Why it matters:** A free, resonant tone carries better and sounds pleasant without forcing.
- **Common misconception:** *"A breathy or forced tone is more expressive."* **Correction:** A free, supported tone is healthiest and most flexible; expression comes from dynamics and phrasing, not strain.
- **Practice cue:** Sing "ng → ah" and feel the buzz/vibration move to the front of the face.','{"tone":4,"quality":1,"resonance":3,"definition":1,"the":10,"timbre":1,"colour":1,"voice":1,"how":3,"warm":1,"bright":1,"clear":1,"focused":1,"sounds":3,"sound":1,"vibrates":2,"and":8,"amplifies":1,"throat":2,"mouth":1,"head":1,"spaces":1,"cue":2,"keep":1,"vowels":1,"tall":1,"open":1,"soft":1,"palate":1,"lifted":1,"start":1,"yawn":1,"relaxed":1,"free":3,"analogy":1,"like":1,"hollow":1,"body":1,"guitar":1,"same":1,"string":1,"fuller":1,"because":1,"space":1,"why":1,"matters":1,"resonant":1,"carries":1,"better":1,"pleasant":1,"without":1,"forcing":1,"common":1,"misconception":1,"breathy":1,"forced":1,"more":1,"expressive":1,"correction":1,"supported":1,"healthiest":1,"most":1,"flexible":1,"expression":1,"comes":1,"from":1,"dynamics":1,"phrasing":1,"not":1,"strain":1,"practice":1,"sing":1,"feel":1,"buzz":1,"vibration":1,"move":1,"front":1,"face":1}'::jsonb),
('chunk_0c7b40cc41bc27a00b','file_c7904436411b2e478c','music.md','4.5 Blending & balance in ensemble','- **Definition:** **Blending** = matching your vowel, tone, and volume to others so voices sound unified. **Balance** = adjusting so no part is too loud or too soft relative to the whole.
- **How-to cue:** Listen more than you sing; match vowel shapes; avoid sticking out; a harmony part supports and sits under the melody.
- **Why it matters:** A choir should sound like one instrument, not many soloists.
- **Common misconception:** *"The best singer should be the loudest."* **Correction:** In ensemble, the goal is to blend — loudness that sticks out breaks the unified sound.
- **Practice cue:** If you can''t hear the person next to you, you''re singing too loud.','{"blending":2,"balance":2,"ensemble":2,"definition":1,"matching":1,"your":1,"vowel":2,"tone":1,"and":2,"volume":1,"others":1,"voices":1,"sound":3,"unified":2,"adjusting":1,"part":2,"too":3,"loud":2,"soft":1,"relative":1,"the":7,"whole":1,"how":1,"cue":2,"listen":1,"more":1,"than":1,"you":4,"sing":1,"match":1,"shapes":1,"avoid":1,"sticking":1,"out":2,"harmony":1,"supports":1,"sits":1,"under":1,"melody":1,"why":1,"matters":1,"choir":1,"should":2,"like":1,"one":1,"instrument":1,"not":1,"many":1,"soloists":1,"common":1,"misconception":1,"best":1,"singer":1,"loudest":1,"correction":1,"goal":1,"blend":1,"loudness":1,"that":1,"sticks":1,"breaks":1,"practice":1,"can":1,"hear":1,"person":1,"next":1,"singing":1}'::jsonb),
('chunk_729b7ac7ec5f3ab696','file_c7904436411b2e478c','music.md','4.6 Vocal health','- **Definition:** Habits that protect the voice from strain and injury.
- **How-to cue:** Warm up before singing; stay hydrated; avoid shouting/screaming; rest the voice when tired or sick; never push through pain.
- **Why it matters:** The voice is a lifelong instrument you cannot replace — protect it.
- **Common misconception:** *"Straining and pushing builds a stronger voice."* **Correction:** Pain or hoarseness is a warning sign; strength comes from good technique and gradual practice, not force.
- **Practice cue:** If your throat hurts or your voice is hoarse, stop and rest — do not push.

