('chunk_6a3cd8b1e9d0b7c931','file_c7904436411b2e478c','music.md','5. Sub-topic C — Music Literacy','Learning to read music is like learning to read words — the symbols tell you the pitch (how high/low) and the rhythm (how long) of each sound.','{"sub":1,"topic":1,"music":2,"literacy":1,"learning":2,"read":2,"like":1,"words":1,"the":3,"symbols":1,"tell":1,"you":1,"pitch":1,"how":2,"high":1,"low":1,"and":1,"rhythm":1,"long":1,"each":1,"sound":1}'::jsonb),
('chunk_55233d058b93ce1427','file_c7904436411b2e478c','music.md','5.1 The staff (stave)','- **Definition:** The set of **5 lines and 4 spaces** on which notes are written. Higher on the staff = higher pitch.
- **Example:** A note sitting on the bottom line is lower than a note on the top line.
- **Practice cue:** Point to two notes and say which sounds higher based on its position.','{"the":5,"staff":2,"stave":1,"definition":1,"set":1,"lines":1,"and":2,"spaces":1,"which":2,"notes":2,"are":1,"written":1,"higher":3,"pitch":1,"example":1,"note":2,"sitting":1,"bottom":1,"line":2,"lower":1,"than":1,"top":1,"practice":1,"cue":1,"point":1,"two":1,"say":1,"sounds":1,"based":1,"its":1,"position":1}'::jsonb),
('chunk_fe8aad8cda1940cf7b','file_c7904436411b2e478c','music.md','5.2 Treble clef','- **Definition:** The symbol at the start of the staff (also called the **G clef**) that fixes the note names; its curl circles the line for the note **G**.
- **Note names on the treble staff:**
  - **Lines** (bottom→top): **E – G – B – D – F** ("Every Good Boy Deserves Fun").
  - **Spaces** (bottom→top): **F – A – C – E** (spells "FACE").
- **Analogy:** The clef is like a "key" that tells you which letters the lines and spaces stand for.
- **Practice cue:** Name three notes on the staff using the line/space mnemonics.','{"treble":2,"clef":3,"definition":1,"the":12,"symbol":1,"start":1,"staff":3,"also":1,"called":1,"that":2,"fixes":1,"note":3,"names":2,"its":1,"curl":1,"circles":1,"line":2,"for":2,"lines":2,"bottom":2,"top":2,"every":1,"good":1,"boy":1,"deserves":1,"fun":1,"spaces":2,"spells":1,"face":1,"analogy":1,"like":1,"key":1,"tells":1,"you":1,"which":1,"letters":1,"and":1,"stand":1,"practice":1,"cue":1,"name":1,"three":1,"notes":1,"using":1,"space":1,"mnemonics":1}'::jsonb),
('chunk_68443cecb7e175e2be','file_c7904436411b2e478c','music.md','5.3 Note names & the musical alphabet','- **Definition:** Pitches are named with the letters **A B C D E F G**, then repeat. After G, it starts again at A.
- **Example:** Going up from C: C–D–E–F–G–A–B–C (an octave).
- **Misconception:** *"There are notes called H."* **Correction:** The English musical alphabet only uses **A–G**; it cycles.
- **Practice cue:** Say the alphabet forward and backward: A-B-C-D-E-F-G and G-F-E-D-C-B-A.','{"note":1,"names":1,"the":4,"musical":2,"alphabet":3,"definition":1,"pitches":1,"are":2,"named":1,"with":1,"letters":1,"then":1,"repeat":1,"after":1,"starts":1,"again":1,"example":1,"going":1,"from":1,"octave":1,"misconception":1,"there":1,"notes":1,"called":1,"correction":1,"english":1,"only":1,"uses":1,"cycles":1,"practice":1,"cue":1,"say":1,"forward":1,"and":2,"backward":1}'::jsonb),
('chunk_e72fd7d58ba2315aea','file_c7904436411b2e478c','music.md','5.4 Note & rest values','- **Definition:** Symbols showing how long a sound (note) or silence (rest) lasts, measured in **beats**.

| Note | Name (US / UK) | Beats in 4/4 | Matching rest |
|------|----------------|--------------|---------------|
| ○ (open, no stem) | Whole / Semibreve | **4 beats** | Whole rest |
| ♩ with open head | Half / Minim | **2 beats** | Half rest |
| ♩ (filled, stem) | Quarter / Crotchet | **1 beat** | Quarter rest |
| ♪ (filled, flag) | Eighth / Quaver | **½ beat** | Eighth rest |

- **Analogy (fractions):** A whole note is a whole pizza; two halves make a whole; four quarters make a whole; eight eighths make a whole.
- **Misconception:** *"A rest means stop playing/relax."* **Correction:** A rest is **counted silence** — you keep the beat internally and stay in time.
- **Practice cue:** Clap a quarter note (1 clap = 1 beat), then two eighths (2 claps in 1 beat: "1-and").','{"note":5,"rest":9,"values":1,"definition":1,"symbols":1,"showing":1,"how":1,"long":1,"sound":1,"silence":2,"lasts":1,"measured":1,"beats":4,"name":1,"matching":1,"open":2,"stem":2,"whole":7,"semibreve":1,"with":1,"head":1,"half":2,"minim":1,"filled":2,"quarter":3,"crotchet":1,"beat":5,"flag":1,"eighth":2,"quaver":1,"analogy":1,"fractions":1,"pizza":1,"two":2,"halves":1,"make":3,"four":1,"quarters":1,"eight":1,"eighths":2,"misconception":1,"means":1,"stop":1,"playing":1,"relax":1,"correction":1,"counted":1,"you":1,"keep":1,"the":1,"internally":1,"and":2,"stay":1,"time":1,"practice":1,"cue":1,"clap":2,"then":1,"claps":1}'::jsonb),
('chunk_1b4cf768fe9f1a0f47','file_c7904436411b2e478c','music.md','5.5 Time signatures','- **Definition:** The two stacked numbers after the clef. **Top number = beats per bar; bottom number = which note gets one beat** (4 = quarter note).
- **Examples:**
  - **4/4** ("common time") = 4 quarter-note beats per bar. Feels like: 1-2-3-4. Most pop and folk songs.
  - **3/4** = 3 quarter-note beats per bar. Feels like a waltz: 1-2-3, strong-weak-weak.
- **Misconception:** *"The bottom number is how many beats there are."* **Correction:** The **top** number is how many beats per bar; the bottom tells you *what kind* of note gets the beat.
- **Practice cue:** Count "1-2-3-4" for 4/4 and "1-2-3" for 3/4, stamping on beat 1.','{"time":2,"signatures":1,"definition":1,"the":6,"two":1,"stacked":1,"numbers":1,"after":1,"clef":1,"top":2,"number":4,"beats":5,"per":4,"bar":4,"bottom":3,"which":1,"note":5,"gets":2,"one":1,"beat":3,"quarter":3,"examples":1,"common":1,"feels":2,"like":2,"most":1,"pop":1,"and":2,"folk":1,"songs":1,"waltz":1,"strong":1,"weak":2,"misconception":1,"how":2,"many":2,"there":1,"are":1,"correction":1,"tells":1,"you":1,"what":1,"kind":1,"practice":1,"cue":1,"count":1,"for":2,"stamping":1}'::jsonb),
('chunk_30dfb07ceb1635831d','file_c7904436411b2e478c','music.md','5.6 Beat & rhythm','- **Definition:** The **beat** is the steady, regular pulse (like a heartbeat). **Rhythm** is the pattern of long and short sounds that plays over the beat.
- **Example:** Beat = a metronome ticking evenly; rhythm = the varied pattern of the words in "Twinkle, Twinkle."
- **Analogy:** The beat is the footsteps; the rhythm is the dance done over those steps.
- **Misconception:** *"Beat and rhythm are the same thing."* **Correction:** Beat is the constant pulse; rhythm is the changing pattern on top of it.
- **Practice cue:** Tap the steady beat with your foot while clapping the rhythm of a song''s words.','{"beat":8,"rhythm":7,"definition":1,"the":15,"steady":2,"regular":1,"pulse":2,"like":1,"heartbeat":1,"pattern":3,"long":1,"and":2,"short":1,"sounds":1,"that":1,"plays":1,"over":2,"example":1,"metronome":1,"ticking":1,"evenly":1,"varied":1,"words":2,"twinkle":2,"analogy":1,"footsteps":1,"dance":1,"done":1,"those":1,"steps":1,"misconception":1,"are":1,"same":1,"thing":1,"correction":1,"constant":1,"changing":1,"top":1,"practice":1,"cue":1,"tap":1,"with":1,"your":1,"foot":1,"while":1,"clapping":1,"song":1}'::jsonb),
('chunk_eeeb4294317d7cb295','file_c7904436411b2e478c','music.md','5.7 Tempo','- **Definition:** The **speed** of the beat, often given in Italian terms or in BPM (beats per minute).
- **Common terms:** *Largo* (very slow), *Adagio* (slow), *Andante* (walking pace), *Moderato* (moderate), *Allegro* (fast, lively), *Presto* (very fast). *Accelerando* = getting faster; *ritardando/rallentando* = getting slower.
- **Example:** A lullaby is *Adagio*; a celebration song is *Allegro*.
- **Misconception:** *"Faster music is always more exciting/better."* **Correction:** Tempo serves the mood — a slow tempo can be powerful and moving.
- **Practice cue:** Sing one phrase at *Andante*, then at *Allegro*, and describe how the feeling changes.','{"tempo":3,"definition":1,"the":4,"speed":1,"beat":1,"often":1,"given":1,"italian":1,"terms":2,"bpm":1,"beats":1,"per":1,"minute":1,"common":1,"largo":1,"very":2,"slow":3,"adagio":2,"andante":2,"walking":1,"pace":1,"moderato":1,"moderate":1,"allegro":3,"fast":2,"lively":1,"presto":1,"accelerando":1,"getting":2,"faster":2,"ritardando":1,"rallentando":1,"slower":1,"example":1,"lullaby":1,"celebration":1,"song":1,"misconception":1,"music":1,"always":1,"more":1,"exciting":1,"better":1,"correction":1,"serves":1,"mood":1,"can":1,"powerful":1,"and":2,"moving":1,"practice":1,"cue":1,"sing":1,"one":1,"phrase":1,"then":1,"describe":1,"how":1,"feeling":1,"changes":1}'::jsonb),
('chunk_889cf6bd3b9bfde4ea','file_c7904436411b2e478c','music.md','5.8 Dynamics','- **Definition:** How **loud or soft** the music is.

| Marking | Italian term | Meaning |
|---------|--------------|---------|
| **pp** | pianissimo | very soft |
| **p** | piano | soft |
| **mp** | mezzo-piano | medium soft |
| **mf** | mezzo-forte | medium loud |
| **f** | forte | loud |
| **ff** | fortissimo | very loud |
| **<** | crescendo | gradually getting louder |
| **>** | decrescendo / diminuendo | gradually getting softer |

- **Analogy:** Dynamics are like the volume knob and the light dimmer of a song — they add shadow and shine.
- **Misconception:** *"Singing louder = singing better."* **Correction:** Great singing uses a *range* of dynamics; soft, controlled singing is often harder and more expressive than loud singing.
- **Practice cue:** Sing one line with a crescendo (soft→loud), then a decrescendo (loud→soft).','{"dynamics":3,"definition":1,"how":1,"loud":7,"soft":7,"the":3,"music":1,"marking":1,"italian":1,"term":1,"meaning":1,"pianissimo":1,"very":2,"piano":2,"mezzo":2,"medium":2,"forte":2,"fortissimo":1,"crescendo":2,"gradually":2,"getting":2,"louder":2,"decrescendo":2,"diminuendo":1,"softer":1,"analogy":1,"are":1,"like":1,"volume":1,"knob":1,"and":3,"light":1,"dimmer":1,"song":1,"they":1,"add":1,"shadow":1,"shine":1,"misconception":1,"singing":5,"better":1,"correction":1,"great":1,"uses":1,"range":1,"controlled":1,"often":1,"harder":1,"more":1,"expressive":1,"than":1,"practice":1,"cue":1,"sing":1,"one":1,"line":1,"with":1,"then":1}'::jsonb);